included.description:
To better understand the iterative design process, we were tasked to create an "experience prototype" of an idea or project. We decided to tackle the museum-going experience. The problem space that we focused on was museum accessibility: how do make the wealth of human knowledge held in the most prestigious museums available to those who can't visit them?

Piggybacking off of progress in augmented reality (AR) field made by the British Museum and the Smithsonian's X 3D imaging project, MARM was envisioned to create a low-cost and interactive exhibition of the Smithsonian Institute's collections in small-towns across the United States. Using AR glasses and gloves, users are able to interact with highly-detailed renderings of artifacts. Simultaneously, they are able to access text, audio, and video lessons about the context and the history of the artifacts by interacting with the exhibition.

We were able to go from concept to experience prototype in the period of four days. To mimic the complex nature that MARM is set to provide, we created a "Wizard of Oz" prototype. Using a series of linked slides on PowerPoint, we had users put on wearables and interact with a series of exhibitions. Behind the scenes, I synchronized the PowerPoint with their gestures to make it seem as if the users were controlling the AR exhibit. This chicanery was necessary to assess the finer points of MARM without having to invest excessive time and money building a true implementation of MARM to get feedback. Our users were engaged with MARM and we hope to make it a reality some day.
included.title: Mobile Augmented Reality Museum (MARM)

For my HCDE 300 class we produced a high fidelity prototype of a mobile application designed for the University of Washington community.

The app provides users with a fast and easy to use system for finding dining option around campus based on user preferences. Interaction design principles and user research drove many of our design decisions for the app. My primary role was to surveys usability tests which guided the direction of our redesign process. Each prototype we made took into account the results of our research in order to further improve our product. I also had a hand in creating the mockups for our project. To create the prototype we used UXPin.com (a design tool).
